"A deadline set Tuesday under federal law essentially locks in President-elect Joe Biden’s victory, even though President Donald Trump is still falsely claiming he won reelection ... Other than Wisconsin, every state appears to have met the safe harbor deadline, which means Congress has to accept the electoral votes that will be cast next week and sent to the Capitol for counting on Jan. 6. Those votes will elect Biden as the country’s next president ... Missing the deadline won’t deprive Wisconsin of its 10 electoral votes. Biden electors still will meet in Madison on Monday to cast their votes and there’s no reason to expect that Congress won’t accept them. In any case, Biden would still have more than the 270 votes he needs even without Wisconsin’s." https://apnews.com/article/safe-harbor-law-locks-congress-joe-biden-119b6e1570f33af0baee1493cbbe012b

Baseline is 54 (1.85%) of presidential elections prior to the 2020 election and since 1804 (inclusive). Only one has relied on the 12th amendment (1824). This one does appear to be formulating as contested in such as manner that it will result in a 12th Amendment situation.

(Initial forecast:) A long-shot (nightmare-) scenario even for 2020 (+ beyond). But primarily because current polling + political forecasting indicates that Donald Trump likely will not be strongly competitive in 2020's Electoral College. Election prognosticators would need to be almost completely wrong, and/or an unforeseen 'black swan' event (somehow 'favoring' Trump) suddenly impacts the U.S. election.

The last time the House of Rep had to get involved in the Presidential vote was in 1824 and it was largely due to two other candidates that pulled significant electoral votes from the two leading candidates. This race is largely between only two candidates and one seems to have a widening, significant lead over the other in polls as of now. I think the odds of one party not getting the required 131 electoral votes is slim.
While nothing is impossible, this is a truly Black Swan possibility - so much so I’m surprised it was even asked
